begin_memory_text: We talked about taking cruises and the different destinations that we have taken cruises from.  We also talked about the difference between Disney and Carnival.  We even discussed taking a cruise during the pandemic.
middle_memory_text: We spoke about the military and our views on the military.  We talked about going to museums and seeing the different planes.  We also spoke about the ICON A-5 and how it also a boat/plane.  We mentioned there is a plane in that looks like a car.
end_memory_text: We talked about the issues with our Internet.  I mentioned that I had my Internet disconnected, and I'm worried that it might happen again.  We briefly talked about the price of the Internet, with and without TV.
rest_of_day_open: I have to work the rest of this week.  I'm probably going to early vote this next week.  I'm hoping to spend some time this week relaxing.  I might also try and get a flu shot this week, and hope there are no issues.  I'm probably going to see if there are ways, I can make some extra money.
critical_positive: I think my partner and I were able to keep the conversation going.  We seemed to be able to find common ground with the topics we were discussing.  It didn't seem like there was any point, when we were just trying to think about what happens next.  We were able to talk freely.
critical_negative: I felt that we didn't have a set list of topics to talk about.  We spent a few moments trying to figure out, what to discuss.  There was some time that I felt that I didn't know what to say next.  We had a little trouble at first trying to get the conversation started.

begin_memory_text: We talked about various platforms we have used to spend our spare time making little bits of money online, including Prolific and MTurk. He talked about what it was like to do MTurk (that he was surprised he got in because it's often full), and I talked about a friend who did audio transcription with Rec. We talked about whether we had each done this task before (he had, I hadn't). We briefly talked about our jobs other than those tasks.
middle_memory_text: We talked about various military bases and briefly mentioned members of our families who were in the military. We discussed whether Chicago had any military bases remaining, and we also discussed different types of planes we had seen in two different museums/air show types places we had each been to. I mentioned a plane from the 1960s that was able to convert to a car (but looked dangerous to me) and he mentioned a new plane that could land on water that had been marketed for private ownership more recently, called something like the Icon. There were issues with the more recent plane sales due to the company not wanting purchasers to resell their planes.
end_memory_text: We talked about Jeopardy, and I talked about a YouTube channel I watch where British men solve Sudokus. We then talked about internet companies, their various charges and what we pay for things, and he told a story about how Comcast came to do something with his neighbor's line and they disconnected his internet instead. He ended that story by saying now whenever he sees a Comcast truck, he wonders whether he's still going to have internet after it drove by, which I thought was funny.
rest_of_day_open: I have a lot of work to do at a new temporary job I'm learning about, and I need to get as much of that work done (or at least be trained for it) this week as I can. I'm going on a trip for the following 2.5 weeks, so I also have to be packing the right things into my car so that I can maintain myself and my business during that time. In other words, this week will be busy, and hectic, and hopefully I will be able to get everything done that I need to. I'm expecting myself to do a good job with preparations, but also to forget some things that I'll have to deal with later.
critical_positive:
I like to ask questions when I'm first meeting somebody, and my conversational partner seemed to take those in stride. I don't feel that either of us asked overly personal questions or shared too many details for a first meeting, and I do think that comfort levels (mine, at least) got better as the conversation went on. We were able to find a few points of mutual moderate interest to talk about. Most of what we discussed fell into the category of information exchange, to me, which is a mode of conversation I'm usually comfortable with. With my best friends, I discuss emotional and intellectual things in a lot of depth, but when first getting to know someone, I've learned that that's an inappropriate way to approach a new friendship or a casual conversation, so I rely more heavily on information exchange as a form of "small talk." 
Small talk that involves exchanging opinions or that's stereotypically about the weather isn't something I consider myself as adept at. Walking away from a conversation with new knowledge or something interesting to think about and maybe look up feels like a success to me.
critical_negative:
There were a few stalled points in the conversation, which I acknowledged out loud. Because I perceived my partner as less active in the conversation, I considered it my responsibility to think of new questions to ask or things to say. I think of it as my job normally to draw out the person I'm talking to until they seem to feel comfortable enough to settle into a rapport.
While I was trying to think of new things to say, I know my eyes were wandering off of the screen. I'm not sure how my conversational partner would have felt about that, if he would have perceived me as inattentive or felt self conscious about it. On the other hand, the lack of his eyes wandering (to my recollection) was part of what made me perceive him as less active in trying to establish and maintain a connection in the conversation. 
I felt pressured by the study to keep the conversation up, but I also don't feel that this was an artificial example of what I would be like in a conversation with a new person at a party or on a blind date or elsewhere. I don't feel that the situation itself caused the conversational lags we sometimes had, nor that it significantly increased my feeling that it was my job to keep the conversation going.
